# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-emr
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The core of Apache Hadoop consists of a storage part, known as Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS), and a processing part which is a MapReduce programming model.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Hadoop splits files into large blocks and distributes them across nodes in a cluster.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] It then transfers packaged code into nodes to process the data in parallel.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] This approach takes advantage of data locality, where nodes manipulate the data they have access to.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] This allows the dataset to be processed faster and more efficiently than it would be in a more conventional supercomputer architecture that relies on a parallel file system where computation and data are distributed via high-speed networking.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Apache Hadoop's MapReduce and HDFS components were inspired by Google papers on MapReduce and Google File System.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The Hadoop framework itself is mostly written in the Java programming language, with some native code in C and command line utilities written as shell scripts.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Perl language can be easily used with Hadoop Streaming to implement the map and reduce parts of the user's program.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] According to its co-founders, Doug Cutting and Mike Cafarella, the idea of Hadoop was conceived in the Google File System paper that was published in October 2003.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The concept was extended in the Google paper *"MapReduce: Simplified Data Processing on Large Clusters".* Development started on the Apache Nutch project, but was moved to the new Hadoop subproject in January 2006.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Doug Cutting, who was working at Yahoo! at the time, named it after his son's toy elephant.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The initial code that was factored out of Nutch consisted of about 5,000 lines of code for HDFS and about 6,000 lines of code for MapReduce.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] In March 2006, Owen O'Malley was the first committer to add to the Hadoop project; Hadoop 0.1.0 was released in April 2006.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] It continues to evolve through contributions that are being made to the project.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The first design document for the Hadoop Distributed File System was written by Dhruba Borthakur in 2007.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Hadoop consists of the *Hadoop Common* package, which provides file system and operating system level abstractions, a MapReduce engine (either MapReduce/MR1 or YARN/MR2) and the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS).
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The Hadoop Common package contains the Java Archive (JAR) files and scripts needed to start Hadoop.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] For effective scheduling of work, every Hadoop-compatible file system should provide location awareness, which is the name of the rack, specifically the network switch where a worker node is.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Hadoop applications can use this information to execute code on the node where the data is, and, failing that, on the same rack/switch to reduce backbone traffic.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] HDFS uses this method when replicating data for data redundancy across multiple racks.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] This approach reduces the impact of a rack power outage or switch failure; if any of these hardware failures occurs, the data will remain available.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] A small Hadoop cluster includes a single master and multiple worker nodes.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The master node consists of a Job Tracker, Task Tracker, NameNode, and DataNode.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] A slave or *worker node* acts as both a DataNode and TaskTracker, though it is possible to have data-only and compute-only worker nodes.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] These are normally used only in nonstandard applications.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Hadoop requires the Java Runtime Environment (JRE) 1.6 or higher.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The standard startup and shutdown scripts require that Secure Shell (SSH) be set up between nodes in the cluster.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] In a larger cluster, HDFS nodes are managed through a dedicated NameNode server to host the file system index, and a secondary NameNode that can generate snapshots of the namenode's memory structures, thereby preventing file-system corruption and loss of data.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Similarly, a standalone JobTracker server can manage job scheduling across nodes.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] When Hadoop MapReduce is used with an alternate file system, the NameNode, secondary NameNode, and DataNode architecture of HDFS are replaced by the file-system-specific equivalents.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The *Hadoop distributed file system* (HDFS) is a distributed, scalable, and portable file system written in Java for the Hadoop framework.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] A Hadoop instance is divided into HDFS and MapReduce.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] HDFS is used for storing the data and MapReduce is used for processing data.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Top three are Master Services/Daemons/Nodes and bottom two are Slave Services.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Master Services can communicate with each other and in the same way Slave services can communicate with each other.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Name Node is a master node and Data node is its corresponding Slave node and can talk with each other.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Hadoop cluster has nominally a single namenode plus a cluster of datanodes, although redundancy options are available for the namenode due to its criticality.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Each datanode serves up blocks of data over the network using a block protocol specific to HDFS.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The file system uses TCP/IP sockets for communication.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Clients use remote procedure calls (RPC) to communicate with each other.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] HDFS stores large files (typically in the range of gigabytes to terabytes) across multiple machines.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] It achieves reliability by replicating the data across multiple hosts, and hence theoretically does not require redundant array of independent disks (RAID) storage on hosts (but to increase input-output (I/O) performance some RAID configurations are still useful).
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] With the default replication value, 3, data is stored on three nodes: two on the same rack, and one on a different rack.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Data nodes can talk to each other to rebalance data, to move copies around, and to keep the replication of data high.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] HDFS is not fully POSIX-compliant, because the requirements for a POSIX file-system differ from the target goals of a Hadoop application.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The trade-off of not having a fully POSIX-compliant file-system is increased performance for data throughput and support for non-POSIX operations such as Append.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] In May 2012, high-availability capabilities were added to HDFS, letting the main metadata server called the NameNode manually fail-over onto a backup.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The project has also started developing automatic fail-overs.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The HDFS file system includes a so-called *secondary namenode*, a misleading term that some might incorrectly interpret as a backup namenode when the primary namenode goes offline.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] In fact, the secondary namenode regularly connects with the primary namenode and builds snapshots of the primary namenode's directory information, which the system then saves to local or remote directories.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] These checkpointed images can be used to restart a failed primary namenode without having to replay the entire journal of file-system actions, then to edit the log to create an up-to-date directory structure.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Because the namenode is the single point for storage and management of metadata, it can become a bottleneck for supporting a huge number of files, especially a large number of small files.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] HDFS Federation, a new addition, aims to tackle this problem to a certain extent by allowing multiple namespaces served by separate namenodes.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Moreover, there are some issues in HDFS such as small file issues, scalability problems, Single Point of Failure (SPoF), and bottlenecks in huge metadata requests.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] One advantage of using HDFS is data awareness between the job tracker and task tracker.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The job tracker schedules map or reduce jobs to task trackers with an awareness of the data location.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] For example: if node A contains data (a, b, c) and node X contains data (x, y, z), the job tracker schedules node A to perform map or reduce tasks on (a, b, c) and node X would be scheduled to perform map or reduce tasks on (x, y, z).
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] This reduces the amount of traffic that goes over the network and prevents unnecessary data transfer.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] When Hadoop is used with other file systems, this advantage is not always available.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] This can have a significant impact on job-completion times as demonstrated with data-intensive jobs.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] HDFS was designed for mostly immutable files and may not be suitable for systems requiring concurrent write operations.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] HDFS can be mounted directly with a Filesystem in Userspace (FUSE) virtual file system on Linux and some other Unix systems.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] File access can be achieved through the native Java API, the Thrift API (generates a client in a number of languages e.g.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] C++, Java, Python, PHP, Ruby, Erlang, Perl, Haskell, C#, Cocoa, Smalltalk, and OCaml), the command-line interface, the HDFS-UI web application over HTTP, or via 3rd-party network client libraries.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] HDFS is designed for portability across various hardware platforms and for compatibility with a variety of underlying operating systems.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The HDFS design introduces portability limitations that result in some performance bottlenecks, since the Java implementation cannot use features that are exclusive to the platform on which HDFS is running.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Due to its widespread integration into enterprise-level infrastructure, monitoring HDFS performance at scale has become an increasingly important issue.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Monitoring end-to-end performance requires tracking metrics from datanodes, namenodes, and the underlying operating system.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] There are currently several monitoring platforms to track HDFS performance, including Hortonworks, Cloudera, and Datadog.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Hadoop works directly with any distributed file system that can be mounted by the underlying operating system by simply using a `file://` URL; however, this comes at a price – the loss of locality.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] To reduce network traffic, Hadoop needs to know which servers are closest to the data, information that Hadoop-specific file system bridges can provide.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] A number of third-party file system bridges have also been written, none of which are currently in Hadoop distributions.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] However, some commercial distributions of Hadoop ship with an alternative file system as the default – specifically IBM and MapR.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Atop the file systems comes the MapReduce Engine, which consists of one *JobTracker*, to which client applications submit MapReduce jobs.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The JobTracker pushes work to available *TaskTracker* nodes in the cluster, striving to keep the work as close to the data as possible.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] With a rack-aware file system, the JobTracker knows which node contains the data, and which other machines are nearby.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] If the work cannot be hosted on the actual node where the data resides, priority is given to nodes in the same rack.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] This reduces network traffic on the main backbone network.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] If a TaskTracker fails or times out, that part of the job is rescheduled.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The TaskTracker on each node spawns a separate Java virtual machine (JVM) process to prevent the TaskTracker itself from failing if the running job crashes its JVM.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] A heartbeat is sent from the TaskTracker to the JobTracker every few minutes to check its status.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The Job Tracker and TaskTracker status and information is exposed by Jetty and can be viewed from a web browser.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] If one TaskTracker is very slow, it can delay the entire MapReduce job – especially towards the end, when everything can end up waiting for the slowest task.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] With speculative execution enabled, however, a single task can be executed on multiple slave nodes.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] By default Hadoop uses FIFO scheduling, and optionally 5 scheduling priorities to schedule jobs from a work queue.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] In version 0.19 the job scheduler was refactored out of the JobTracker, while adding the ability to use an alternate scheduler (such as the *Fair scheduler* or the *Capacity scheduler*, described next).
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The fair scheduler was developed by Facebook.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The goal of the fair scheduler is to provide fast response times for small jobs and quality of service (QoS) for production jobs.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The fair scheduler has three basic concepts.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Each pool is assigned a guaranteed minimum share.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] By default, jobs that are uncategorized go into a default pool.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Pools have to specify the minimum number of map slots, reduce slots, as well as a limit on the number of running jobs.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The capacity scheduler was developed by Yahoo.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The capacity scheduler supports several features that are similar to those of the fair scheduler.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Free resources are allocated to queues beyond their total capacity.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Within a queue, a job with a high level of priority has access to the queue's resources.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] There is no preemption once a job is running.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The biggest difference between Hadoop 1 and Hadoop 2 is the addition of YARN (Yet Another Resource Negotiator), which replaced the MapReduce engine in the first version of Hadoop.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] YARN strives to allocate resources to various applications effectively.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] It runs two daemons, which take care of two different tasks: the *resource manager*, which does job tracking and resource allocation to applications, the *application master*, which monitors progress of the execution.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] There are important features provided by Hadoop 3.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] For example, while there is one single *namenode* in Hadoop 2, Hadoop 3, enables having multiple name nodes, which solves the single point of failure problem.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] In Hadoop 3, there are containers working in principle of Docker, which reduces time spent on application development.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] One of the biggest changes is that Hadoop 3 decreases storage overhead with erasure coding.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Also, Hadoop 3 permits usage of GPU hardware within the cluster, which is a very substantial benefit to execute deep learning algorithms on a Hadoop cluster.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The HDFS is not restricted to MapReduce jobs.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] It can be used for other applications, many of which are under development at Apache.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] The list includes the HBase database, the Apache Mahout machine learning system, and the Apache Hive data warehouse.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Theoretically, Hadoop could be used for any workload that is batch-oriented rather than real-time, is very data-intensive, and benefits from parallel processing.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] It can also be used to complement a real-time system, such as lambda architecture, Apache Storm, Flink, and Spark Streaming.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Inc. launched what they claimed was the world's largest Hadoop production application.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Search Webmap is a Hadoop application that runs on a Linux cluster with more than 10,000 cores and produced data that was used in every Yahoo! web search query.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] There are multiple Hadoop clusters at Yahoo! and no HDFS file systems or MapReduce jobs are split across multiple data centers.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Every Hadoop cluster node bootstraps the Linux image, including the Hadoop distribution.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Work that the clusters perform is known to include the index calculations for the Yahoo! search engine.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] In June 2009, Yahoo! made the source code of its Hadoop version available to the open-source community.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] In 2010, Facebook claimed that they had the largest Hadoop cluster in the world with 21 PB of storage.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] In June 2012, they announced the data had grown to 100 PB and later that year they announced that the data was growing by roughly half a PB per day.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] As of 2013, Hadoop adoption had become widespread: more than half of the Fortune 50 companies used Hadoop.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] Influential papers on the birth, growth, and curation of Hadoop and big data processing include: Jeffrey Dean, Sanjay Ghemawat (2004) MapReduce: Simplified Data Processing on Large Clusters, Google.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] This paper inspired Doug Cutting to develop an open-source implementation of the Map-Reduce framework.
[src:aws-emr/amazon-emr] He named it Hadoop, after his son's toy elephant.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Hive provides the necessary SQL abstraction to integrate SQL-like queries (HiveQL) into the underlying Java without the need to implement queries in the low-level Java API.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Hive facilitates the integration of SQL-based querying languages with Hadoop, which is commonly used in data warehousing applications.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] While initially developed by Facebook, Apache Hive is used and developed by other companies such as Netflix and the Financial Industry Regulatory Authority (FINRA).
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Amazon maintains a software fork of Apache Hive included in Amazon Elastic MapReduce on Amazon Web Services.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Apache Hive supports the analysis of large datasets stored in Hadoop's HDFS and compatible file systems such as Amazon S3 filesystem and Alluxio.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] It provides a SQL-like query language called HiveQL with schema on read and transparently converts queries to MapReduce, Apache Tez and Spark jobs.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] All three execution engines can run in Hadoop's resource negotiator, YARN (Yet Another Resource Negotiator).
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] By default, Hive stores metadata in an embedded Apache Derby database, and other client/server databases like MySQL can optionally be used.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] The first four file formats supported in Hive were plain text, sequence file, optimized row columnar (ORC) format and RCFile.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Apache Parquet can be read via plugin in versions later than 0.10 and natively starting at 0.13.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Major components of the Hive architecture include the metastore, driver, compiler, optimizer, executor, and user interfaces.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] The **metastore** stores metadata for each of the tables, such as their schema and location.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] It also includes partition metadata which helps the driver to track the progress of various data sets distributed over the cluster.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] The data is stored in a traditional RDBMS format.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] This metadata enables the driver to keep track of the data.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] A backup server regularly replicates the data to provide recovery in case of data loss.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] The **driver** acts like a controller which receives the HiveQL statements.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] It starts the execution of the statement by creating sessions and monitors the life cycle and progress of the execution.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] It stores the necessary metadata generated during the execution of a HiveQL statement.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] The driver also acts as a collection point of data or query results obtained after the Reduce operation.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] The **compiler** performs compilation of the HiveQL query, converting the query to an execution plan.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] This plan contains the tasks and steps needed to be performed by the Hadoop MapReduce to get the output as translated by the query.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] The compiler converts the query to an abstract syntax tree (AST).
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] After checking for compatibility and compile time errors, it converts the AST to a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] The DAG divides operators to MapReduce stages and tasks based on the input query and data.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] The **optimizer** performs various transformations on the execution plan to produce an optimized DAG.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Transformations can be aggregated together, such as converting a pipeline of joins to a single join, for better performance.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] It can also split tasks, such as applying a transformation on data before a reduce operation, to provide better performance and scalability.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] The logic of transformation used for optimization can be modified or pipelined using another optimizer.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] An optimizer called YSmart is a part of Apache Hive.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] This correlated optimizer merges correlated MapReduce jobs into a single MapReduce job, significantly reducing the execution time.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] The **executor** executes the tasks after compilation and optimization.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] It interacts with the job tracker of Hadoop to schedule tasks to be run.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] It takes care of pipelining the tasks by making sure that a task with a dependency gets executed only if all other prerequisites have been completed.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] A command-line interface (CLI) provides a user interface for an external user to interact with Hive by submitting queries and instructions and monitoring the process status.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] The **Thrift Server** allows external clients to interact with Hive over a network, similar to the JDBC or ODBC protocols.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] While based on SQL, HiveQL does not strictly follow the full SQL-92 standard.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] HiveQL offers extensions not in SQL, including *multi-table inserts,* and *creates tables as select*.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] HiveQL lacked support for transactions and materialized views, and offered only limited subquery support.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Support for insert, update, and delete with full ACID functionality was made available with release 0.14.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Internally, a compiler translates HiveQL statements into a directed acyclic graph of MapReduce, Tez, or Spark jobs, which are submitted to Hadoop for execution.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] The word count program counts the number of times each word occurs in the input.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Checks if table docs exists and drops it if it does.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Creates a new table called docs with a single column of type STRING called line.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Loads the specified file or directory (In this case “input_file”) into the table.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] OVERWRITE specifies that the target table to which the data is being loaded into is to be re-written; Otherwise, the data would be appended.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] The query `CREATE TABLE word_counts AS SELECT word, count(1) AS count` creates a table called word_counts with two columns: word and count.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] This query draws its input from the inner query `(SELECT explode(split(line, '\s')) AS word FROM docs) temp`, which splits the input words into different rows of a temporary table aliased as temp.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] The `GROUP BY WORD` clause groups the results based on their keys, so that the count column holds the number of occurrences for each word of the word column.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] The `ORDER BY WORDS` clause sorts the words alphabetically.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] The storage and querying operations of Hive resemble those of traditional relational databases.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Although Hive utilizes an SQL-like dialect, differences exist in its structure and operation because it is built on top of the Hadoop ecosystem and operates within the design characteristics of Hadoop and MapReduce.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] A schema is applied to a table in traditional databases.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] In such traditional databases, the table typically enforces the schema when the data is loaded into the table.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] This enables the database to make sure that the data entered follows the representation of the table as specified by the table definition.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] This design is called *schema on write*.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] In comparison, Hive does not verify the data against the table schema on write.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Instead, it subsequently does run time checks when the data is read.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] The two approaches have their own advantages and drawbacks.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Checking data against a table schema during load time adds operational overhead, meaning traditional databases require more time to load data.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Verification checks are performed during loading to detect corrupt data prior to query execution.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Because data validation occurs during or immediately after the load stage, subsequent query performance is optimized.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] In contrast, Hive loads data without initial schema verification, resulting in faster data loading but slower query execution times.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Hive can be utilized when the schema is unavailable during data ingestion and is instead defined dynamically at run time.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Transactions are key operations in traditional databases.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] As any typical RDBMS, Hive supports all four properties of transactions (ACID): Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, and Durability.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Transactions in Hive were introduced in Hive 0.13 but were only limited to the partition level.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] The recent version of Hive 0.14 had these functions fully added to support complete ACID properties.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Hive 0.14 and later provides different row level transactions such as *INSERT, DELETE and UPDATE*.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Enabling *INSERT, UPDATE, and DELETE* transactions require setting appropriate values for configuration properties such as `hive.support.concurrency`, `hive.enforce.bucketing`, and `hive.exec.dynamic.partition.mode`.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Hive v0.7.0 added integration with Hadoop security.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Hadoop began using Kerberos authorization support to provide security.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Kerberos allows for mutual authentication between client and server, where the client's request for a ticket is passed along with the request.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] In earlier versions of Hadoop, users could modify usernames via the `hadoop.job.ugi` property, and MapReduce operations ran under a shared default user identity (such as Hadoop or mapred).
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Following Hive v0.7.0's integration with Hadoop security, TaskTracker jobs are executed by the user who initiated them, and the username can no longer be spoofed by setting the `hadoop.job.ugi` property.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] Permissions for newly created files in Hive are dictated by the HDFS.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] The Hadoop distributed file system authorization model uses three entities: user, group and others with three permissions: read, write and execute.
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] The default permissions for newly created files can be set by changing the unmask value for the Hive configuration variable `hive.files.umask.value`..
[src:aws-emr/apache-hive] The default permissions for newly created files can be set by changing the unmask value for the Hive configuration variable `hive.files.umask.value`.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Apache Spark has its architectural foundation in the resilient distributed dataset (RDD), a read-only multiset of data items distributed over a cluster of machines, that is maintained in a fault-tolerant way.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] The Dataframe API was released as an abstraction on top of the RDD, followed by the Dataset API.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] In Spark 1.x, the RDD was the primary application programming interface (API), but as of Spark 2.x use of the Dataset API is encouraged even though the RDD API is not deprecated.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] The RDD technology still underlies the Dataset API.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Spark's RDDs function as a working set for distributed programs that offers a (deliberately) restricted form of distributed shared memory.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Inside Apache Spark the workflow is managed as a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Nodes represent RDDs while edges represent the operations on the RDDs.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Spark facilitates the implementation of both iterative algorithms, which visit their data set multiple times in a loop, and interactive/exploratory data analysis, i.e., the repeated database-style querying of data.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] The latency of such applications may be reduced by several orders of magnitude compared to Apache Hadoop MapReduce implementation.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Among the class of iterative algorithms are the training algorithms for machine learning systems, which formed the initial impetus for developing Apache Spark.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Apache Spark requires a cluster manager and a distributed storage system.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] For cluster management, Spark supports standalone native Spark, Hadoop YARN, Apache Mesos or Kubernetes.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] A standalone native Spark cluster can be launched manually or by the launch scripts provided by the install package.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] It is also possible to run the daemons on a single machine for testing.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] For distributed storage Spark can interface with a wide variety of distributed systems, including Alluxio, Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS), MapR File System (MapR-FS), Cassandra, OpenStack Swift, Amazon S3, Kudu, Lustre file system, or a custom solution can be implemented.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Spark also supports a pseudo-distributed local mode, usually used only for development or testing purposes, where distributed storage is not required and the local file system can be used instead; in such a scenario, Spark is run on a single machine with one executor per CPU core.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Spark Core is the foundation of the overall project.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] This interface mirrors a functional/higher-order model of programming: a "driver" program invokes parallel operations such as map, filter or reduce on an RDD by passing a function to Spark, which then schedules the function's execution in parallel on the cluster.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] These operations, and additional ones such as joins, take RDDs as input and produce new RDDs.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] RDDs are immutable and their operations are lazy; fault-tolerance is achieved by keeping track of the "lineage" of each RDD (the sequence of operations that produced it) so that it can be reconstructed in the case of data loss.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] RDDs can contain any type of Python, .NET, Java, or Scala objects.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Besides the RDD-oriented functional style of programming, Spark provides two restricted forms of shared variables: *broadcast variables* reference read-only data that needs to be available on all nodes, while *accumulators* can be used to program reductions in an imperative style.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] A typical example of RDD-centric functional programming is the following Scala program that computes the frequencies of all words occurring in a set of text files and prints the most common ones.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Each map, flatMap (a variant of map) and reduceByKey takes an anonymous function that performs a simple operation on a single data item (or a pair of items), and applies its argument to transform an RDD into a new RDD.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] PySpark is the Python API for Apache Spark, introduced in Spark 0.7, released in February 2013.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] It allows Spark applications to be written in Python and provides an interactive shell for exploratory analysis.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] PySpark code executes under the standard CPython runtime and can call native Python libraries such as NumPy and SciPy; communication between Python user code and Spark's JVM-based core has historically been mediated by the Py4J library.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] PySpark provides Python interfaces to most of Spark's components, including Spark Core, Spark SQL and the DataFrame API, Structured Streaming, and MLlib; since Spark 4.1 it also exposes the Spark Declarative Pipelines API.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] A pandas-compatible API, known as *pandas API on Spark*, was integrated into PySpark in Apache Spark 3.2.0, released in October 2021.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] It provides equivalents to the pandas data-analysis API that execute against the Spark engine, allowing pandas-style code to be run on distributed data.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] The component originated as Koalas, a separate project open-sourced by Databricks in 2019, which was subsequently merged into PySpark.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] PySpark also provides a client for Spark Connect, a client–server architecture that enables remote connectivity to Spark clusters from PySpark applications.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Spark SQL is a component on top of Spark Core that introduced a data abstraction called DataFrames, which provides support for structured and semi-structured data.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Spark SQL provides a domain-specific language (DSL) to manipulate DataFrames in Scala, Java, Python or .NET.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] It also provides SQL language support, with command-line interfaces and ODBC/JDBC server.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Although DataFrames lack the compile-time type-checking afforded by RDDs, as of Spark 2.0, the strongly typed DataSet is fully supported by Spark SQL as well.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Spark Declarative Pipelines (SDP) is a declarative framework for defining and running extract, transform, load (ETL) data pipelines, added in Apache Spark 4.1.0, which was released on December 16, 2025.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Developers declare the datasets a pipeline should produce and the queries that define them, rather than writing imperative code specifying how each dataset is computed and in what order; Spark constructs a dataflow graph and manages dependency ordering, parallelism, checkpointing, and retries.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] The framework extends Spark's lazy, declarative execution model, previously applied to individual queries through Spark SQL, to pipelines spanning multiple datasets.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Pipelines are defined in SQL or Python and are organized around streaming tables and materialized views, with the underlying transformations expressed as "flows"; batch and streaming computations can be combined within a single pipeline.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Spark Structured Streaming uses Spark Core's fast scheduling capability to perform streaming analytics.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] It ingests data in micro-batches and performs RDD transformations on those micro-batches of data.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] This design enables the same set of application code written for batch analytics to be used in streaming analytics, thus facilitating easy implementation of lambda architecture.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] However, this convenience comes with the penalty of latency equal to the mini-batch duration.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Other streaming data engines that process event by event rather than in micro-batches include Storm and the streaming component of Flink.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Spark Streaming has support built-in to consume from Kafka, Flume, Twitter, ZeroMQ, Kinesis, and TCP/IP sockets.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] In Spark 2.x, a separate technology based on Datasets, called Structured Streaming, that has a higher-level interface is also provided to support streaming.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Apache Spark 4.x added a Real-Time Mode (RTM) execution model for Structured Streaming, with the stated goal of lowering end-to-end latency to support operational and batch workloads on a single engine.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Existing Structured Streaming queries written against the DataFrame and Dataset APIs can be executed under the new mode without modification to the query.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Spark can be deployed in a traditional on-premises data center as well as in the cloud.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Spark Connect is a decoupled client–server architecture for Apache Spark that allows remote applications to connect to a Spark cluster from any environment, introduced in Apache Spark 3.4, released in April 2023.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] The architecture separates the client application from the Spark driver, which historically ran in the same process; under Spark Connect, the client is a thin library that can be embedded in application servers, IDEs, notebooks and other programming environments.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Results are streamed back to the client as Apache Arrow-encoded row batches.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] PySpark support for Spark Connect was added in Spark 3.4, and Scala client support followed in Spark 3.5; additional clients for languages including Go, Swift and Rust have been developed in later releases.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] GraphX is a distributed graph-processing framework on top of Apache Spark.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Because it is based on RDDs, which are immutable, graphs are immutable and thus GraphX is unsuitable for graphs that need to be updated, let alone in a transactional manner like a graph database.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] GraphX provides two separate APIs for implementation of massively parallel algorithms (such as PageRank): a Pregel abstraction, and a more general MapReduce-style API.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Unlike its predecessor Bagel, which was formally deprecated in Spark 1.6, GraphX has full support for property graphs (graphs where properties can be attached to edges and vertices).
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Like Apache Spark, GraphX initially started as a research project at UC Berkeley's AMPLab and Databricks, and was later donated to the Apache Software Foundation and the Spark project.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Apache Spark has built-in support for Scala, Java, SQL, R, Python, and Swift with 3rd party support for the .NET CLR, Julia, and more.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Spark was initially started by Matei Zaharia at UC Berkeley's AMPLab in 2009, and open sourced in 2010 under a BSD license.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] In 2013, the project was donated to the Apache Software Foundation and switched its license to Apache 2.0.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] In February 2014, Spark became a Top-Level Apache Project.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Zaharia's company Databricks set a new world record in large scale sorting using Spark.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Spark had in excess of 1000 contributors in 2015, making it one of the most active projects in the Apache Software Foundation and one of the most active open source big data projects.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Spark 3.5.2 is based on Scala 2.13 (and thus works with Scala 2.12 and 2.13 out-of-the-box), but it can also be made to work with Scala 3.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Apache Spark is developed by a community.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] The project is managed by a group called the "Project Management Committee" (PMC).
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] Feature release branches will, generally, be maintained with bug fix releases for a period of 18 months.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] For example, branch 2.3.x is no longer considered maintained as of September 2019, 18 months after the release of 2.3.0 in February 2018.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] No more 2.3.x releases should be expected after that point, even for bug fixes.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] The last minor release within a major a release will typically be maintained for longer as an “LTS” release.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] For example, 2.4.0 was released on November 2, 2018, and had been maintained for 31 months until 2.4.8 was released in May 2021.
[src:aws-emr/apache-spark] 2.4.8 is the last release and no more 2.4.x releases should be expected even for bug fixes.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Big data analysis challenges include capturing data, data storage, data analysis, search, sharing, transfer, visualization, querying, updating, information privacy, and data sources.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Big data was originally associated with three key concepts: *volume*, *variety*, and *velocity*.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The analysis of big data that have only volume, velocity, and variety can pose challenges in sampling.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] A fourth concept, *veracity,* which refers to the level of reliability of data, was thus added.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Current usage of the term *big data* tends to refer to the use of predictive analytics, user behavior analytics, or certain other advanced data analytics methods that extract value from big data, and seldom to a particular size of data set.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] "There is little doubt that the quantities of data now available are indeed large, but that's not the most relevant characteristic of this new data ecosystem." Analysis of data sets can find new correlations to "spot business trends, prevent diseases, combat crime and so on".
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Scientists, business executives, medical practitioners, advertising and governments alike regularly meet difficulties with large datasets in areas including Internet searches, fintech, healthcare analytics, geographic information systems, urban informatics, and business informatics.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Scientists encounter limitations in e-Science work, including meteorology, genomics, connectomics, complex physics simulations, biology, and environmental research.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The world's technological per-capita capacity to store information has roughly doubled every 40 months since the 1980s; as of 2012, every day 2.5 exabytes (2.17×260 bytes) of data are generated.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Based on an IDC report prediction, the global data volume was predicted to grow exponentially from 4.4 zettabytes to 44 zettabytes between 2013 and 2020.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] By 2025, IDC predicts there will be 163 zettabytes of data.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] According to IDC, global spending on big data and business analytics (BDA) solutions is estimated to reach $215.7 billion in 2021.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Statista reported that the global big data market is forecasted to grow to $103 billion by 2027.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] In 2011 McKinsey & Company reported, if US healthcare were to use big data creatively and effectively to drive efficiency and quality, the sector could create more than $300 billion in value every year.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] In the developed economies of Europe, government administrators could save more than €100 billion ($149 billion) in operational efficiency improvements alone by using big data.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] And users of services enabled by personal-location data could capture $600 billion in consumer surplus.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] One question for large enterprises is determining who should own big-data initiatives that affect the entire organization.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Relational database management systems and desktop statistical software packages used to visualize data often have difficulty processing and analyzing big data.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The processing and analysis of big data may require "massively parallel software running on tens, hundreds, or even thousands of servers".
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] What qualifies as "big data" varies depending on the capabilities of those analyzing it and their tools.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Furthermore, expanding capabilities make big data a moving target.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] "For some organizations, facing hundreds of gigabytes of data for the first time may trigger a need to reconsider data management options.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The term *big data* has been in use since the 1990s, with some giving credit to John Mashey for popularizing the term.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Big data usually includes data sets with sizes beyond the ability of commonly used software tools to capture, curate, manage, and process data within a tolerable elapsed time.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Big data philosophy encompasses unstructured, semi-structured and structured data; however, the main focus is on unstructured data.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Big data "size" is a constantly moving target; as of 2012 ranging from a few dozen terabytes to many zettabytes of data.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Big data requires a set of techniques and technologies with new forms of integration to reveal insights from datasets that are diverse, complex, and of a massive scale.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Variability is often included as an additional quality of big data.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] In a comparative study of big datasets, Kitchin and McArdle found that none of the commonly considered characteristics of big data appear consistently across all of the analyzed cases.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] For this reason, other studies identified the redefinition of power dynamics in knowledge discovery as the defining trait.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Instead of focusing on the intrinsic characteristics of big data, this alternative perspective pushes forward a relational understanding of the object claiming that what matters is the way in which data is collected, stored, made available and analyzed.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The quantity of generated and stored data.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The size of the data determines the value and potential insight, and whether it can be considered big data or not.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The size of big data is usually larger than terabytes and petabytes.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Earlier technologies like RDBMSs were capable to handle structured data efficiently and effectively.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] However, the change in type and nature from structured to semi-structured or unstructured challenged the existing tools and technologies.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Big data technologies evolved with the prime intention to capture, store, and process the semi-structured and unstructured (variety) data generated with high speed (velocity), and huge in size (volume).
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Later, these tools and technologies were explored and used for handling structured data also but preferable for storage.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Eventually, the processing of structured data was still kept as optional, either using big data or traditional RDBMSs.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] This helps in analyzing data towards effective usage of the hidden insights exposed from the data collected via social media, log files, sensors, etc.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The speed at which the data is generated and processed to meet the demands and challenges that lie in the path of growth and development.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Big data is often available in real-time.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] , big data is produced more continually.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Two kinds of velocity related to big data are the frequency of generation and the frequency of handling, recording, and publishing.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The truthfulness or reliability of the data, which refers to the data quality and the data value.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Big data must not only be large in size, but also must be reliable in order to achieve value in the analysis of it.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] of captured data can vary greatly, affecting an accurate analysis.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The worth in information that can be achieved by the processing and analysis of large datasets.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Value also can be measured by an assessment of the other qualities of big data.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Value may also represent the profitability of information that is retrieved from the analysis of big data.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Unlike variety, variability captures the notion the fact that formats, structure, or sources of big data change through time and given different circumstances.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Interpretation of data depends on a changing context, and with a different context, the old meanings may become invalid.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Big data may or may not include all the available data from sources.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Respectively, the proportion of specific data of each element per element collected and if the element and its characteristics are properly indexed or identified.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] If the data collected contains common fields that would enable a conjoining, or meta-analysis, of different data sets.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] If new fields in each element of the data collected can be added or changed easily.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] If the size of the big data storage system can expand rapidly.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Big data repositories have existed in many forms, often built by corporations with a special need.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Commercial vendors historically offered parallel database management systems for big data beginning in the 1990s.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] For many years, WinterCorp published the largest database report.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Teradata Corporation in 1984 marketed the parallel processing DBC 1012 system.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Teradata systems were the first to store and analyze 1 terabyte of data in 1992.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Hard disk drives were 2.5 GB in 1991 so the definition of big data continuously evolves.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Teradata installed the first petabyte class RDBMS based system in 2007.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] As of 2017, there are a few dozen petabyte class Teradata relational databases installed, the largest of which exceeds 50 PB.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Systems up until 2008 were 100% structured relational data.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Since then, Teradata has added semi structured data types including XML, JSON, and Avro.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] (now LexisNexis Risk Solutions) developed a C++-based distributed platform for data processing and querying known as the HPCC Systems platform.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] This system automatically partitions, distributes, stores and delivers structured, semi-structured, and unstructured data across multiple commodity servers.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Users can write data processing pipelines and queries in a declarative dataflow programming language called ECL.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Data analysts working in ECL are not required to define data schemas upfront and can rather focus on the particular problem at hand, reshaping data in the best possible manner as they develop the solution.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] In 2004, LexisNexis acquired Seisint Inc. and their high-speed parallel processing platform and successfully used this platform to integrate the data systems of Choicepoint Inc. when they acquired that company in 2008.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] In 2011, the HPCC systems platform was open-sourced under the Apache v2.0 License.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] CERN and other physics experiments have collected big data sets for many decades, usually analyzed via high-throughput computing rather than the map-reduce architectures usually meant by the current "big data" movement.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] In 2004, Google published a paper on a process called MapReduce that uses a similar architecture.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The MapReduce concept provides a parallel processing model, and an associated implementation was released to process huge amounts of data.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] With MapReduce, queries are split and distributed across parallel nodes and processed in parallel (the "map" step).
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The results are then gathered and delivered (the "reduce" step).
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The framework was very successful, so others wanted to replicate the algorithm.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Therefore, an implementation of the MapReduce framework was adopted by an Apache open-source project named "Hadoop".
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Apache Spark was developed in 2012 in response to limitations in the MapReduce paradigm, as it adds in-memory processing and the ability to set up many operations (not just map followed by reducing).
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] MIKE2.0 is an open approach to information management that acknowledges the need for revisions due to big data implications identified in an article titled "Big Data Solution Offering".
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The methodology addresses handling big data in terms of useful permutations of data sources, complexity in interrelationships, and difficulty in deleting (or modifying) individual records.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Studies in 2012 showed that a multiple-layer architecture was one option to address the issues that big data presents.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] A distributed parallel architecture distributes data across multiple servers; these parallel execution environments can dramatically improve data processing speeds.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] This type of architecture inserts data into a parallel DBMS, which implements the use of MapReduce and Hadoop frameworks.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] This type of framework looks to make the processing power transparent to the end-user by using a front-end application server.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The data lake allows an organization to shift its focus from centralized control to a shared model to respond to the changing dynamics of information management.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] This enables quick segregation of data into the data lake, thereby reducing the overhead time.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Multidimensional big data can also be represented as OLAP data cubes or, mathematically, tensors.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Array database systems have set out to provide storage and high-level query support on this data type.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Although, many approaches and technologies have been developed, it still remains difficult to carry out machine learning with big data.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Some MPP relational databases have the ability to store and manage petabytes of data.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Implicit is the ability to load, monitor, back up, and optimize the use of the large data tables in the RDBMS.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] DARPA's Topological Data Analysis program seeks the fundamental structure of massive data sets and in 2008 the technology went public with the launch of a company called "Ayasdi".
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The practitioners of big data analytics processes are generally hostile to slower shared storage, preferring direct-attached storage (DAS) in its various forms from solid state drive (SSD) to high capacity SATA disk buried inside parallel processing nodes.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The perception of shared storage architectures—storage area network (SAN) and network-attached storage (NAS)— is that they are relatively slow, complex, and expensive.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] These qualities are not consistent with big data analytics systems that thrive on system performance, commodity infrastructure, and low cost.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Real or near-real-time information delivery is one of the defining characteristics of big data analytics.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Latency is therefore avoided whenever and wherever possible.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Data in direct-attached memory or disk is good—data on memory or disk at the other end of an FC SAN connection is not.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The cost of an SAN at the scale needed for analytics applications is much higher than other storage techniques.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Big data has increased the demand of information management specialists so much so that Software AG, Oracle Corporation, IBM, Microsoft, SAP, EMC, HP, and Dell have spent more than $15 billion on software firms specializing in data management and analytics.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] In 2010, this industry was worth more than $100 billion and was growing at almost 10 percent a year, about twice as fast as the software business as a whole.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Developed economies increasingly use data-intensive technologies.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] There are 4.6 billion mobile-phone subscriptions worldwide, and between 1 billion and 2 billion people accessing the internet.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Between 1990 and 2005, more than 1 billion people worldwide entered the middle class, which means more people became more literate, which in turn led to information growth.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The world's effective capacity to exchange information through telecommunication networks was 281 petabytes in 1986, 471 petabytes in 1993, 2.2 exabytes in 2000, 65 exabytes in 2007 and predictions put the amount of internet traffic at 667 exabytes annually by 2014.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] According to one estimate, one-third of the globally stored information is in the form of alphanumeric text and still image data, which is the format most useful for most big data applications.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] This also shows the potential of yet unused data (i.e. in the form of video and audio content).
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] While many vendors offer off-the-shelf products for big data, experts promote the development of in-house custom-tailored systems if the company has sufficient technical capabilities.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The use and adoption of big data within governmental processes allows efficiencies in terms of cost, productivity, and innovation, but comes with flaws.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Data analysis often requires multiple parts of government (central and local) to work in collaboration and create new and innovative processes to deliver the desired outcome.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] A common government organization that makes use of big data is the National Security Agency (NSA), which monitors the activities of the Internet constantly in search for potential patterns of suspicious or illegal activities their system may pick up.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Civil registration and vital statistics (CRVS) collects all certificates status from birth to death.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] CRVS is a source of big data for governments.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Research on the effective usage of information and communication technologies for development (also known as "ICT4D") suggests that big data technology can make important contributions but also present unique challenges to international development.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Advancements in big data analysis offer cost-effective opportunities to improve decision-making in critical development areas such as health care, employment, economic productivity, crime, security, and natural disaster and resource management.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Additionally, user-generated data offers new opportunities to give the unheard a voice.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] However, longstanding challenges for developing regions such as inadequate technological infrastructure and economic and human resource scarcity exacerbate existing concerns with big data such as privacy, imperfect methodology, and interoperability issues.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The challenge of "big data for development" is currently evolving toward the application of this data through machine learning, known as "artificial intelligence for development (AI4D).
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] A major practical application of big data for development has been "fighting poverty with data".
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] In 2015, Blumenstock and colleagues estimated predicted poverty and wealth from mobile phone metadata and in 2016 Jean and colleagues combined satellite imagery and machine learning to predict poverty.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] At the same time, working with digital trace data instead of traditional survey data does not eliminate the traditional challenges involved in the field of international quantitative analysis.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Priorities may change, but the fundamental discussions remain the same.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Big Data is being rapidly adopted in Finance to 1) speed up processing and 2) deliver better, more informed inferences, both internally and to the clients of the financial institutions.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Big Data has also been a typical concept within the field of alternative financial service.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Some of the major areas involve crowd-funding platforms and crypto currency exchanges.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Some areas of improvement are more aspirational than actually implemented.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The level of data generated within healthcare systems is not trivial.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] With the added adoption of mHealth, eHealth and wearable technologies the volume of data will continue to increase.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] This includes electronic health record data, imaging data, patient generated data, sensor data, and other forms of difficult to process data.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] There is now an even greater need for such environments to pay greater attention to data and information quality.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] While extensive information in healthcare is now electronic, it fits under the big data umbrella as most is unstructured and difficult to use.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The use of big data in healthcare has raised significant ethical challenges ranging from risks for individual rights, privacy and autonomy, to transparency and trust.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Big data in health research is particularly promising in terms of exploratory biomedical research, as data-driven analysis can move forward more quickly than hypothesis-driven research.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Then, trends seen in data analysis can be tested in traditional, hypothesis-driven follow up biological research and eventually clinical research.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] A related application sub-area, that heavily relies on big data, within the healthcare field is that of computer-aided diagnosis in medicine.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] For instance, for epilepsy monitoring it is customary to create 5 to 10 GB of data daily.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Similarly, a single uncompressed image of breast tomosynthesis averages 450 MB of data.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] These are just a few of the many examples where computer-aided diagnosis uses big data.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] For this reason, big data has been recognized as one of the seven key challenges that computer-aided diagnosis systems need to overcome in order to reach the next level of performance.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] A McKinsey Global Institute study found a shortage of 1.5 million highly trained data professionals and managers and a number of universities including University of Tennessee and UC Berkeley, have created masters programs to meet this demand.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Private boot camps have also developed programs to meet that demand, including paid programs like The Data Incubator or General Assembly.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] In the specific field of marketing, one of the problems stressed by Wedel and Kannan is that marketing has several sub domains (e.g., advertising, promotions, product development, branding) that all use different types of data.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] To understand how the media uses big data, it is first necessary to provide some context into the mechanism used for media process.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] It has been suggested by Nick Couldry and Joseph Turow that practitioners in media and advertising approach big data as many actionable points of information about millions of individuals.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The industry appears to be moving away from the traditional approach of using specific media environments such as newspapers, magazines, or television shows and instead taps into consumers with technologies that reach targeted people at optimal times in optimal locations.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The ultimate aim is to serve or convey, a message or content that is (statistically speaking) in line with the consumer's mindset.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] For example, publishing environments are increasingly tailoring messages (advertisements) and content (articles) to appeal to consumers that have been exclusively gleaned through various data-mining activities.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Channel 4, the British public-service television broadcaster, is a leader in the field of big data and data analysis.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Health insurance providers are collecting data on social "determinants of health" such as food and TV consumption, marital status, clothing size, and purchasing habits, from which they make predictions on health costs, in order to spot health issues in their clients.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] It is controversial whether these predictions are currently being used for pricing.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Big data and the IoT work in conjunction.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Data extracted from IoT devices provides a mapping of device inter-connectivity.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Such mappings have been used by the media industry, companies, and governments to more accurately target their audience and increase media efficiency.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The IoT is also increasingly adopted as a means of gathering sensory data, and this sensory data has been used in medical, manufacturing and transportation contexts.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Especially since 2015, big data has come to prominence within business operations as a tool to help employees work more efficiently and streamline the collection and distribution of information technology (IT).
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The use of big data to resolve IT and data collection issues within an enterprise is called IT operations analytics (ITOA).
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] By applying big data principles into the concepts of machine intelligence and deep computing, IT departments can predict potential issues and prevent them.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] ITOA businesses offer platforms for systems management that bring data silos together and generate insights from the whole of the system rather than from isolated pockets of data.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Compared to survey-based data collection, big data has low cost per data point, applies analysis techniques via machine learning and data mining, and includes diverse and new data sources, e.g., registers, social media, apps, and other forms digital data.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Since 2018, survey scientists have started to examine how big data and survey science can complement each other to allow researchers and practitioners to improve the production of statistics and its quality.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] In 2021, the founding members of BigSurv received the Warren J.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Mitofsky Innovators Award from the American Association for Public Opinion Research.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Big data is notable in marketing due to the constant "datafication" of everyday consumers of the internet, in which all forms of data are tracked.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The datafication of consumers can be defined as quantifying many of or all human behaviors for the purpose of marketing.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The increasingly digital world of rapid datafication makes this idea relevant to marketing because the amount of data constantly grows exponentially.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] It is predicted to increase from 44 to 163 zettabytes within the span of five years.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The size of big data can often be difficult to navigate for marketers.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] As a result, adopters of big data may find themselves at a disadvantage.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Algorithmic findings can be difficult to achieve with such large datasets.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Big data in marketing is a highly lucrative tool that can be used for large corporations, its value being as a result of the possibility of predicting significant trends, interests, or statistical outcomes in a consumer-based manner.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Real-time market responsiveness is important for marketers because of the ability to shift marketing efforts and correct to current trends, which is helpful in maintaining relevance to consumers.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] This can supply corporations with the information necessary to predict the wants and needs of consumers in advance.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Data-driven market ambidexterity are being highly fueled by big data.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] New models and algorithms are being developed to make significant predictions about certain economic and social situations.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Big data can be used to improve training and understanding competitors, using sport sensors.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] It is also possible to predict winners in a match using big data analytics.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Future performance of players could be predicted as well.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Thus, players' value and salary is determined by data collected throughout the season.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] In Formula One races, race cars with hundreds of sensors generate terabytes of data.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] These sensors collect data points from tire pressure to fuel burn efficiency.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Based on the data, engineers and data analysts decide whether adjustments should be made in order to win a race.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Besides, using big data, race teams try to predict the time they will finish the race beforehand, based on simulations using data collected over the season.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] During the COVID-19 pandemic, big data was raised as a way to minimise the impact of the disease.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Significant applications of big data included minimizing the spread of the virus, case identification and development of medical treatment.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Governments used big data to track infected people to minimise spread.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Early adopters included China, Taiwan, South Korea, and Israel.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Encrypted search and cluster formation in big data were demonstrated in March 2014 at the American Society of Engineering Education.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Gautam Siwach engaged at *Tackling the challenges of Big Data* by MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory and Amir Esmailpour at the UNH Research Group investigated the key features of big data as the formation of clusters and their interconnections.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] They focused on the security of big data and the orientation of the term towards the presence of different types of data in an encrypted form at cloud interface by providing the raw definitions and real-time examples within the technology.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Moreover, they proposed an approach for identifying the encoding technique to advance towards an expedited search over encrypted text leading to the security enhancements in big data.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] In March 2012, The White House announced a national "Big Data Initiative" that consisted of six federal departments and agencies committing more than $200 million to big data research projects.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The initiative included a National Science Foundation "Expeditions in Computing" grant of $10 million over five years to the AMPLab at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The AMPLab also received funds from DARPA, and over a dozen industrial sponsors and uses big data to attack a wide range of problems from predicting traffic congestion to fighting cancer.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The White House Big Data Initiative also included a commitment by the Department of Energy to provide $25 million in funding over five years to establish the Scalable Data Management, Analysis and Visualization (SDAV) Institute, led by the Energy Department's Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The SDAV Institute aims to bring together the expertise of six national laboratories and seven universities to develop new tools to help scientists manage and visualize data on the department's supercomputers.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The U.S. state of Massachusetts announced the Massachusetts Big Data Initiative in May 2012, which provides funding from the state government and private companies to a variety of research institutions.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The Massachusetts Institute of Technology hosts the Intel Science and Technology Center for Big Data in the MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, combining government, corporate, and institutional funding and research efforts.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The European Commission is funding the two-year-long Big Data Public Private Forum through their Seventh Framework Program to engage companies, academics and other stakeholders in discussing big data issues.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The project aims to define a strategy in terms of research and innovation to guide supporting actions from the European Commission in the successful implementation of the big data economy.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Outcomes of this project will be used as input for Horizon 2020, their next framework program.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The British government announced in March 2014 the founding of the Alan Turing Institute, named after the computer pioneer and code-breaker, which will focus on new ways to collect and analyze large data sets.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] At the University of Waterloo Stratford Campus Canadian Open Data Experience (CODE) Inspiration Day, participants demonstrated how using data visualization can increase the understanding and appeal of big data sets and communicate their story to the world.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Computational social sciences – Anyone can use application programming interfaces (APIs) provided by big data holders, such as Google and Twitter, to do research in the social and behavioral sciences.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Tobias Preis et al. used Google Trends data to demonstrate that Internet users from countries with a higher per capita gross domestic products (GDPs) are more likely to search for information about the future than information about the past.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The findings suggest there may be a link between online behaviors and real-world economic indicators.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The authors of the study examined Google queries logs made by ratio of the volume of searches for the coming year (2011) to the volume of searches for the previous year (2009), which they call the "future orientation index".
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] They compared the future orientation index to the per capita GDP of each country, and found a strong tendency for countries where Google users inquire more about the future to have a higher GDP.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Tobias Preis and his colleagues Helen Susannah Moat and H.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Eugene Stanley introduced a method to identify online precursors for stock market moves, using trading strategies based on search volume data provided by Google Trends.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Their analysis of Google search volume for 98 terms of varying financial relevance, published in *Scientific Reports*, suggests that increases in search volume for financially relevant search terms tend to precede large losses in financial markets.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Big data sets come with algorithmic challenges that previously did not exist.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Hence, there is seen by some to be a need to fundamentally change the processing ways.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] A research question that is asked about big data sets is whether it is necessary to look at the full data to draw certain conclusions about the properties of the data or if is a sample is good enough.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] The name big data itself contains a term related to size and this is an important characteristic of big data.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] But sampling enables the selection of right data points from within the larger data set to estimate the characteristics of the whole population.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] In manufacturing different types of sensory data such as acoustics, vibration, pressure, current, voltage, and controller data are available at short time intervals.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] To predict downtime it may not be necessary to look at all the data but a sample may be sufficient.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] Big data can be broken down by various data point categories such as demographic, psychographic, behavioral, and transactional data.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p01] With large sets of data points, marketers are able to create and use more customized segments of consumers for more strategic targeting.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Critiques of the big data paradigm come in two flavors: those that question the implications of the approach itself, and those that question the way it is currently done.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] One approach to this criticism is the field of critical data studies.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Mark Graham has leveled broad critiques at Chris Anderson's assertion that big data will spell the end of theory: focusing in particular on the notion that big data must always be contextualized in their social, economic, and political contexts.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Even as companies invest eight- and nine-figure sums to derive insight from information streaming in from suppliers and customers, less than 40% of employees have sufficiently mature processes and skills to do so.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] To overcome this insight deficit, big data, no matter how comprehensive or well analyzed, must be complemented by "big judgment", according to an article in the *Harvard Business Review*.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Much in the same line, it has been pointed out that the decisions based on the analysis of big data are inevitably "informed by the world as it was in the past, or, at best, as it currently is".
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Fed by a large number of data on past experiences, algorithms can predict future development if the future is similar to the past.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] If the system's dynamics of the future change (if it is not a stationary process), the past can say little about the future.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] In order to make predictions in changing environments, it would be necessary to have a thorough understanding of the systems dynamic, which requires theory.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] As a response to this critique Alemany Oliver and Vayre suggest to use "abductive reasoning as a first step in the research process in order to bring context to consumers' digital traces and make new theories emerge".
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Additionally, it has been suggested to combine big data approaches with computer simulations, such as agent-based models and complex systems.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Agent-based models are increasingly getting better in predicting the outcome of social complexities of even unknown future scenarios through computer simulations that are based on a collection of mutually interdependent algorithms.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Finally, the use of multivariate methods that probe for the latent structure of the data, such as factor analysis and cluster analysis, have proven useful as analytic approaches that go well beyond the bi-variate approaches (e.g. contingency tables) typically employed with smaller data sets.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] In health and biology, conventional scientific approaches are based on experimentation.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] For these approaches, the limiting factor is the relevant data that can confirm or refute the initial hypothesis.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] A new postulate is accepted now in biosciences: the information provided by the data in huge volumes (omics) without prior hypothesis is complementary and sometimes necessary to conventional approaches based on experimentation.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] In the massive approaches it is the formulation of a relevant hypothesis to explain the data that is the limiting factor.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] The search logic is reversed and the limits of induction ("Glory of Science and Philosophy scandal", C.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Privacy advocates are concerned about the threat to privacy represented by increasing storage and integration of personally identifiable information; expert panels have released various policy recommendations to conform practice to expectations of privacy.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] The misuse of big data in several cases by media, companies, and even the government has allowed for abolition of trust in almost every fundamental institution holding up society.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Barocas and Nissenbaum argue that one way of protecting individual users is by being informed about the types of information being collected, with whom it is shared, under what constraints and for what purposes.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] The "V" model of big data is concerning as it centers around computational scalability and lacks in a loss around the perceptibility and understandability of information.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Large data sets have been analyzed by computing machines for well over a century, including the US census analytics performed by IBM's punch-card machines which computed statistics including means and variances of populations across the whole continent.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] In more recent decades, science experiments such as CERN have produced data on similar scales to current commercial "big data".
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Ulf-Dietrich Reips and Uwe Matzat wrote in 2014 that big data had become a "fad" in scientific research.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Researcher danah boyd has raised concerns about the use of big data in science neglecting principles such as choosing a representative sample by being too concerned about handling the huge amounts of data.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] This approach may lead to results that have a bias in one way or another.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Integration across heterogeneous data resources—some that might be considered big data and others not—presents formidable logistical as well as analytical challenges, but many researchers argue that such integrations are likely to represent the most promising new frontiers in science.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] In the provocative article "Critical Questions for Big Data", the authors title big data a part of mythology: "large data sets offer a higher form of intelligence and knowledge [...], with the aura of truth, objectivity, and accuracy".
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Users of big data are often "lost in the sheer volume of numbers", and "working with Big Data is still subjective, and what it quantifies does not necessarily have a closer claim on objective truth".
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Recent developments in BI domain, such as pro-active reporting especially target improvements in the usability of big data, through automated filtering of non-useful data and correlations.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Big data analysis is often shallow compared to analysis of smaller data sets.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] In many big data projects, there is no large data analysis happening, but the challenge is the extract, transform, load part of data pre-processing.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Big data is a buzzword and a "vague term", but at the same time an "obsession" with entrepreneurs, consultants, scientists, and the media.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Big data showcases such as Google Flu Trends failed to deliver good predictions in recent years, overstating the flu outbreaks by a factor of two.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Similarly, Academy Awards and election predictions solely based on Twitter were more often off than on target.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Big data often poses the same challenges as small data; adding more data does not solve problems of bias, but may emphasize other problems.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] In particular data sources such as Twitter are not representative of the overall population, and results drawn from such sources may then lead to wrong conclusions.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Google Translate—which is based on big data statistical analysis of text—does a good job at translating web pages.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] However, results from specialized domains may be dramatically skewed.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] On the other hand, big data may also introduce new problems, such as the multiple comparisons problem: simultaneously testing a large set of hypotheses is likely to produce many false results that mistakenly appear significant.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Furthermore, big data analytics results are only as good as the model on which they are predicated.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] In an example, big data took part in attempting to predict the results of the 2016 U.S. presidential election with varying degrees of success.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Big data has been used in policing and surveillance by institutions like law enforcement and corporations ().
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Due to the less visible nature of data-based surveillance as compared to traditional methods of policing, objections to big data policing are less likely to arise.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] If these potential problems are not corrected or regulated, the effects of big data policing may continue to shape societal hierarchies.
[src:aws-emr/big-data-p02] Brayne also notes that the conscientious use of big data policing could prevent individual-level biases from becoming institutional biases.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] The components of a distributed system communicate and coordinate their actions by passing messages to one another in order to achieve a common goal.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Three challenges of distributed systems are: maintaining concurrency of components, overcoming the lack of a global clock, and managing the independent failure of components.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] When a component of one system fails, the entire system does not fail.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Examples of distributed systems vary from SOA-based systems to microservices to massively multiplayer online games to peer-to-peer applications.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Distributed systems cost more than monolithic architectures, primarily due to increased needs for additional hardware, servers, gateways, firewalls, new subnets, proxies, and so on.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Distributed systems can also suffer from fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Conversely, a well-designed distributed system is more scalable, more durable, more changeable, and more fine-tuned than a monolithic application deployed on a single machine.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] According to Marc Brooker: "a system is scalable in the range where marginal cost of additional workload is nearly constant." Serverless technologies fit this definition but the total cost of ownership, and not just the infrastructure cost must be considered.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] A computer program that runs within a distributed system is called a **distributed program**, and *distributed programming* is the process of writing such programs.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] There are many types of implementations for the message-passing mechanism, including pure HTTP, RPC-like connectors, and message queues.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] The word *distributed* in terms such as "distributed system", "distributed programming", and "distributed algorithm" originally referred to computer networks where individual computers were physically distributed within some geographical area.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] The terms are nowadays used in a much wider sense, even referring to autonomous processes that run on the same physical computer and interact with each other by message passing.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] A distributed system may have a common goal, such as solving a large computational problem; the user then perceives the collection of autonomous processors as a unit.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Alternatively, each computer may have its own user with individual needs, and the purpose of the distributed system is to coordinate the use of shared resources or provide communication services to the users.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] In distributed systems, events represent a fact or state change (e.g., *OrderPlaced*) and are typically broadcast asynchronously to multiple consumers, promoting loose coupling and scalability.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] While events generally don't expect an immediate response, acknowledgment mechanisms are often implemented at the infrastructure level (e.g., Kafka commit offsets, SNS delivery statuses) rather than being an inherent part of the event pattern itself.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] In contrast, messages serve a broader role, encompassing commands (e.g., *ProcessPayment*), events (e.g., *PaymentProcessed*), and documents (e.g., *DataPayload*).
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Both events and messages can support various delivery guarantees, including at-least-once, at-most-once, and exactly-once, depending on the technology stack and implementation.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] However, exactly-once delivery is often achieved through idempotency mechanisms rather than true, infrastructure-level exactly-once semantics.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Delivery patterns for both events and messages include publish/subscribe (one-to-many) and point-to-point (one-to-one).
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] While request/reply is technically possible, it is more commonly associated with messaging patterns rather than pure event-driven systems.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Events excel at state propagation and decoupled notifications, while messages are better suited for command execution, workflow orchestration, and explicit coordination.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Modern architectures commonly combine both approaches, leveraging events for distributed state change notifications and messages for targeted command execution and structured workflows based on specific timing, ordering, and delivery requirements.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Distributed systems are groups of networked computers which share a common goal for their work.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have much overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Parallel computing may be seen as a particularly tightly coupled form of distributed computing, and distributed computing may be seen as a loosely coupled form of parallel computing.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] The figure on the right illustrates the difference between distributed and parallel systems.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Figure (a) is a schematic view of a typical distributed system; the system is represented as a network topology in which each node is a computer and each line connecting the nodes is a communication link.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Figure (b) shows the same distributed system in more detail: each computer has its own local memory, and information can be exchanged only by passing messages from one node to another by using the available communication links.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Figure (c) shows a parallel system in which each processor has a direct access to a shared memory.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] The situation is further complicated by the traditional uses of the terms parallel and distributed *algorithm* that do not quite match the above definitions of parallel and distributed *systems* (see below for more detailed discussion).
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Nevertheless, as a rule of thumb, high-performance parallel computation in a shared-memory multiprocessor uses parallel algorithms while the coordination of a large-scale distributed system uses distributed algorithms.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] The use of concurrent processes which communicate through message-passing has its roots in operating system architectures studied in the 1960s.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] The first widespread distributed systems were local-area networks such as Ethernet, which was invented in the 1970s.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] ARPANET, one of the predecessors of the Internet, was introduced in the late 1960s, and ARPANET e-mail was invented in the early 1970s.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] E-mail became the most successful application of ARPANET, and it is probably the earliest example of a large-scale distributed application.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] In addition to ARPANET (and its successor, the global Internet), other early worldwide computer networks included Usenet and FidoNet from the 1980s, both of which were used to support distributed discussion systems.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] The study of distributed computing became its own branch of computer science in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] The first conference in the field, Symposium on Principles of Distributed Computing (PODC), dates back to 1982, and its counterpart International Symposium on Distributed Computing (DISC) was first held in Ottawa in 1985 as the International Workshop on Distributed Algorithms on Graphs.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Various hardware and software architectures are used for distributed computing.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] At a lower level, it is necessary to interconnect multiple CPUs with some sort of network, regardless of whether that network is printed onto a circuit board or made up of loosely coupled devices and cables.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] At a higher level, it is necessary to interconnect processes running on those CPUs with some sort of communication system.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Distributed programming typically falls into one of several basic architectures: client–server, three-tier, *n*-tier, or peer-to-peer; or categories: loose coupling, or tight coupling.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Another basic aspect of distributed computing architecture is the method of communicating and coordinating work among concurrent processes.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Through various message passing protocols, processes may communicate directly with one another, typically in a main/sub relationship.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Alternatively, a "database-centric" architecture can enable distributed computing to be done without any form of direct inter-process communication, by utilizing a shared database.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Database-centric architecture in particular provides relational processing analytics in a schematic architecture allowing for live environment relay.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] This enables distributed computing functions both within and beyond the parameters of a networked database.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing approach in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Each cell operates independently, processing requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] A cell typically consists of multiple services or application components and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Some implementations replicate entire sets of services across multiple cells, while others partition workloads between cells.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] In replicated models, requests may be rerouted to an operational cell if another experiences a failure.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] This design is intended to enhance system resilience by reducing the impact of localized failures.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Some implementations employ circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to prevent cascading failures among services, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in some large-scale distributed systems, particularly in cloud-native and high-availability environments, where fault isolation and redundancy are key design considerations.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Its implementation varies depending on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and operational objectives.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] According to Reactive Manifesto, reactive distributed systems are responsive, resilient, elastic and message-driven.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Subsequently, Reactive systems are more flexible, loosely-coupled and scalable.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] To make your systems reactive, you are advised to implement Reactive Principles.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Reactive Principles are a set of principles and patterns which help to make your cloud native application as well as edge native applications more reactive.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Many tasks that we would like to automate by using a computer are of question–answer type: we would like to ask a question and the computer should produce an answer.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] In theoretical computer science, such tasks are called computational problems.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Formally, a computational problem consists of *instances* together with a *solution* for each instance.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Instances are questions that we can ask, and solutions are desired answers to these questions.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Theoretical computer science seeks to understand which computational problems can be solved by using a computer (computability theory) and how efficiently (computational complexity theory).
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Traditionally, it is said that a problem can be solved by using a computer if we can design an algorithm that produces a correct solution for any given instance.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Such an algorithm can be implemented as a computer program that runs on a general-purpose computer: the program reads a problem instance from input, performs some computation, and produces the solution as output.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Formalisms such as random-access machines or universal Turing machines can be used as abstract models of a sequential general-purpose computer executing such an algorithm.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] The field of concurrent and distributed computing studies similar questions in the case of either multiple computers, or a computer that executes a network of interacting processes: which computational problems can be solved in such a network and how efficiently?
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] However, it is not at all obvious what is meant by "solving a problem" in the case of a concurrent or distributed system: for example, what is the task of the algorithm designer, and what is the concurrent or distributed equivalent of a sequential general-purpose computer?
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] The discussion below focuses on the case of multiple computers, although many of the issues are the same for concurrent processes running on a single computer.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] In the case of distributed algorithms, computational problems are typically related to graphs.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Often the graph that describes the structure of the computer network *is* the problem instance.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] This is illustrated in the following example.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Consider the computational problem of finding a coloring of a given graph *G*.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] While the field of parallel algorithms has a different focus than the field of distributed algorithms, there is much interaction between the two fields.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] For example, the Cole–Vishkin algorithm for graph coloring was originally presented as a parallel algorithm, but the same technique can also be used directly as a distributed algorithm.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Moreover, a parallel algorithm can be implemented either in a parallel system (using shared memory) or in a distributed system (using message passing).
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] The traditional boundary between parallel and distributed algorithms (choose a suitable network vs. run in any given network) does not lie in the same place as the boundary between parallel and distributed systems (shared memory vs. message passing).
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] In parallel algorithms, yet another resource in addition to time and space is the number of computers.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Indeed, often there is a trade-off between the running time and the number of computers: the problem can be solved faster if there are more computers running in parallel (see speedup).
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] If a decision problem can be solved in polylogarithmic time by using a polynomial number of processors, then the problem is said to be in the class NC.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] The class NC can be defined equally well by using the PRAM formalism or Boolean circuits—PRAM machines can simulate Boolean circuits efficiently and vice versa.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] In the analysis of distributed algorithms, more attention is usually paid on communication operations than computational steps.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Perhaps the simplest model of distributed computing is a synchronous system where all nodes operate in a lockstep fashion.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] This model is commonly known as the LOCAL model.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] During each *communication round*, all nodes in parallel (1) receive the latest messages from their neighbours, (2) perform arbitrary local computation, and (3) send new messages to their neighbors.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] In such systems, a central complexity measure is the number of synchronous communication rounds required to complete the task.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] This complexity measure is closely related to the diameter of the network.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] On the one hand, any computable problem can be solved trivially in a synchronous distributed system in approximately 2*D* communication rounds: simply gather all information in one location (*D* rounds), solve the problem, and inform each node about the solution (*D* rounds).
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] On the other hand, if the running time of the algorithm is much smaller than *D* communication rounds, then the nodes in the network must produce their output without having the possibility to obtain information about distant parts of the network.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] In other words, the nodes must make globally consistent decisions based on information that is available in their *local D-neighbourhood*.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Many distributed algorithms are known with the running time much smaller than *D* rounds, and understanding which problems can be solved by such algorithms is one of the central research questions of the field.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Typically an algorithm which solves a problem in polylogarithmic time in the network size is considered efficient in this model.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Another commonly used measure is the total number of bits transmitted in the network (cf. communication complexity).
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] The features of this concept are typically captured with the CONGEST(B) model, which is similarly defined as the LOCAL model, but where single messages can only contain B bits.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Traditional computational problems take the perspective that the user asks a question, a computer (or a distributed system) processes the question, then produces an answer and stops.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] However, there are also problems where the system is required not to stop, including the dining philosophers problem and other similar mutual exclusion problems.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] In these problems, the distributed system is supposed to continuously coordinate the use of shared resources so that no conflicts or deadlocks occur.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] There are also fundamental challenges that are unique to distributed computing, for example those related to *fault-tolerance*.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Examples of related problems include consensus problems, Byzantine fault tolerance, and self-stabilisation.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Note that in distributed systems, latency should be measured through "99th percentile" because "median" and "average" can be misleading.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] The network nodes communicate among themselves in order to decide which of them will get into the "coordinator" state.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] For that, they need some method in order to break the symmetry among them.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] For example, if each node has unique and comparable identities, then the nodes can compare their identities, and decide that the node with the highest identity is the coordinator.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] The definition of this problem is often attributed to LeLann, who formalized it as a method to create a new token in a token ring network in which the token has been lost.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Coordinator election algorithms are designed to be economical in terms of total bytes transmitted, and time.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] The algorithm suggested by Gallager, Humblet, and Spira for general undirected graphs has had a strong impact on the design of distributed algorithms in general, and won the Dijkstra Prize for an influential paper in distributed computing.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Many other algorithms were suggested for different kinds of network graphs, such as undirected rings, unidirectional rings, complete graphs, grids, directed Euler graphs, and others.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] A general method that decouples the issue of the graph family from the design of the coordinator election algorithm was suggested by Korach, Kutten, and Moran.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] In order to perform coordination, distributed systems employ the concept of coordinators.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] The coordinator election problem is to choose a process from among a group of processes on different processors in a distributed system to act as the central coordinator.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] Several central coordinator election algorithms exist.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] So far the focus has been on *designing* a distributed system that solves a given problem.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] A complementary research problem is *studying* the properties of a given distributed system.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] The halting problem is an analogous example from the field of centralised computation: we are given a computer program and the task is to decide whether it halts or runs forever.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] The halting problem is undecidable in the general case, and naturally understanding the behaviour of a computer network is at least as hard as understanding the behaviour of one computer.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] However, there are many interesting special cases that are decidable.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] In particular, it is possible to reason about the behaviour of a network of finite-state machines.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] One example is telling whether a given network of interacting (asynchronous and non-deterministic) finite-state machines can reach a deadlock.
[src:aws-emr/distributed-computing] This problem is PSPACE-complete, i.e., it is decidable, but not likely that there is an efficient (centralised, parallel or distributed) algorithm that solves the problem in the case of large networks.
